Negative effect of disclosure on sellers (the Option Value effect) is a
 form of seller coordination failure.
 In a marketplace where sellers act independently, each seller keeps his
 schedule open by rejecting low-value jobs to increase his individual chances
 of getting high-value jobs.
 As a result, sellers spend a lot of time waiting for the high-value jobs.
 Collectively, this behavior is suboptimal because all profitable jobs have
 to be completed.
 The source of the coordination failure is what I call the 
\emph on
cream-skimming externality
\emph default
: By rejecting a job, a seller remains available on the marketplace and
 attracts a fraction of subsequent buyers, who otherwise would go the other
 sellers.
 As a result, the other sellers face fewer profitable jobs and obtain lower
 profits.
 
\end_layout

